ABSTRACT
This article provides a number of information about the importance of critical-analytical thinking and
the opinions and researches of international experts on its development. Critical-analytical thinking is
also discussed in which areas of research are based. Also, the recommendations of well-known
researchers on the development of critical-analytical thinking competence, the concept of reflexivity and
its importance in various fields, and the possibilities of developing critical thinking based on
metacognitive activity are discussed. This article serves as a basic source of information for researchers
and educators on the problem of critical-analytical thinking.

The term critical thinking has been used in the peda-
gogical environment for a long time, and different educators
understand it in different ways. For most educators and
methodologists, critical thinking means higher-order
thinking. High means that he is at the last high level of
learning abilities according to Benjamin Bloom's system. By
critical thinking, philosophers generally mean the logical
thinking and reasoning skills that enable students to read
carefully, engage in deep discussion, and express their
ideas clearly and thoughtfully in writing. For literary
theorists and historians, a critical approach to a text is
one that helps to isolate the components of a text and to
critically re-examine the ways in which the text affects the
reader and to determine the authors reasons for creating
the work.

although experts in psychology and related disciplines

critical thinking is the use of cognitive methods or strategies
that increase the likelihood of achieving a desired

The term critical thinking is known from the works of
famous psychologists Jean Piaget and L.Vygotsky, it is still
mainly because of the everyday ideas about critical thinking
that it is a negative thing, a negation, rejection, opposition

that the development of critical thinking has become one of

is the importance of knowing facts, laws, historical dates
and events, but the ability to meaningfully work with
information, distinguish the main ideas in it, see the
relationship between them, choose and reject what is

for future practical work in a rapidly changing world [2].
Critical thinking begins with posing a question and
identify- ing a problem that needs to be solved. Humans
are curious by nature. When we notice something new, we
certainly want to know its essence. When we see a
historical monument, we want to go inside it. In all the
animal world, writes the chemist and philosopher Michael
Polonius, from its simplest form, the worm, perhaps even
the amoeba, we find the act of literary caution, the activity
of inquiry that does not depend on the immediate
satisfaction of need: any living creature We observe that he
strives to intelligently control his surroundings [3].
Critical-analytical thinking competence is an essential
skill that allows individuals to analyze situations, evaluate
information, and make informed decisions.

The development of this competence is crucial in
various fields, including education, problem-solving, and
professional growth. Let's explore some foreign
experiences and perspectives on the development of
critical-analytical thinking competence.
Importance of Critical Thinking Skills
Critical thinking skills enable individuals to analyze
situa- tions and find workable solutions. These skills are
highly valued in various contexts, including education and
professional settings[4]. Analytical thinking, a key
component of critical thinking, involves evaluating data
from multiple sources to come to the best conclusions.
Open-mindedness is another critical thinking skill that helps
individuals analyze and process information to arrive at
unbiased conclusions [5].
Foreign Experiences on Developing Critical-Analyti-
cal Thinking Competence.
Foreign experiences and studies have explored the
development of critical-analytical thinking competence in
different contexts. Here are a few examples:
Development of Critical Thinking in Higher Education.
The training of high-level specialists in higher education
requires the active introduction of pedagogical technologies
that contribute to the development of higher-order thinking
[6].
Critical Thinking in Teaching/Studying Foreign Langua-
ges. A study analyzed the viewpoints of participants in
focus groups discussing critical thinking in teaching and
studying foreign languages [7].
Effects of Diversity Experiences on Critical Thinking
Skills. Research has documented the benefits of student
engagement in diversity experiences on various college
outcomes, including critical thinking skills [8].
Analytical Thinking as a Key Competence. Analytical
thinking is considered a critical component of mental
activity that enables people to solve problems quickly and
effectively [9].
Developing Critical Thinking Competence in English
Majors. In China, the Ministry of Education emphasizes the
development of critical thinking ability in English majors to
enhance their intercultural communicative competence
[10].
Research Competence, Critical Thinking Skills, and
Digital Literacy. Studies have investigated the relationship
between research competence, critical thinking skills, and
engagement with technology in English as a Foreign
Language (EFL) students [11].
These examples highlight the diverse contexts in which
critical-analytical thinking competence is being developed
and studied. The experiences and insights gained from
these studies can contribute to the understanding and
enhancement of critical thinking skills in various
educational and professional settings.
The development of critical-analytical thinking compe-
tence is crucial for individuals to navigate complex
situations, make informed decisions, and excel in their
chosen fields. Foreign experiences and studies provide
valuable insights into the development and enhancement of
these skills. By embracing open-mindedness, analytical
thinking, and other critical thinking skills, individuals can
cultivate their ability to think critically and analytically,
leading to better problem-solving and decision-making
capabilities.
American philosopher and pedagogue J. Dewey said
that only if students begin to deal with a specific problem,
they will develop critical thinking. The most important
question about a situation or event, which is considered the
starting point of the learning process, is the question of
what kind of problem this event creates. Only when
struggling with a specific problem and looking for his own
way out of a difficult situation, the student really thinks.
It can be concluded that, while preparing for the lesson,
the teacher should determine the range of problems that
the students may encounter, and then prepare the students
to formulate these problems on their own.
